        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "Building and deploying ML/AI models is becoming increasingly easier. Most notably LLM's are now widely used for tasks that previously required training specialised ML models and experts with deep expertise to do so. The same trend also happens outside of GenAI with AutoML and more recently prefitted models, such as TabPFN. At the same time, it becames **more** difficult to evaluate the performance of those models and to trace back failure modes. In this article I will discuss the reasons and some of the implications of this trend. \n",
        "\n",
        "## The evolution of training machine learning models\n",
        "\n",
        "In the classical supervised-learning setup, the situation is clean: the\n",
        "dataset has known features **X** and a known target **y**, we hold out a\n",
        "test split, train on the rest, and evaluate predictions against the\n",
        "ground truth with a well-defined metric.\n",
        "\n",
        "```{mermaid}\n",
        "---\n",
        "config:\n",
        "  theme: neutral\n",
        "  layout: elk\n",
        "---\n",
        "flowchart LR\n",
        "    D[\"Labeled dataset <br> X, y\"] --> S{Train / Test <br> split}\n",
        "    S -->|train| TR[Train set]\n",
        "    S -->|test| TE[Test set]\n",
        "    TR --> M[Model training]\n",
        "    M --> F[Fitted model]\n",
        "    TE -->|X_test| F\n",
        "    F -->|y_pred| EV[\"Evaluation <br> e.g. MAE, AUC\"]\n",
        "    TE -->|y_test| EV\n",
        "    EV --> R[Performance <br> score]\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "The key property of this setup is that **everything the model is judged on\n",
        "is unambiguous**: inputs, outputs, and the scoring function are all\n",
        "explicit.\n",
        "\n",
        "## From a one-shot evaluation to a continuous loop\n",
        "\n",
        "In production, evaluation isn't a one-time event. Models drift, data\n",
        "distributions shift, and the system has to be re-checked and retrained on\n",
        "a cadence. This is the classical MLOps loop:\n",
        "\n",
        "```{mermaid}\n",
        "%%| label: fig-mlops\n",
        "%%| fig-cap: \"The classical MLOps loop — train, deploy, monitor, retrain on drift.\"\n",
        "---\n",
        "config:\n",
        "  theme: neutral\n",
        "  layout: elk\n",
        "---\n",
        "flowchart LR\n",
        "    A[Data <br> collection] --> B[Data <br> preparation]\n",
        "    B --> C[Model <br> training]\n",
        "    C --> D[Evaluation]\n",
        "    D --> E[Deployment]\n",
        "    E --> F[Monitoring]\n",
        "    F -.->|drift / decay <br> detected| A\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "Each arrow back from monitoring is where the classical eval story starts\n",
        "to crack — because in many modern setups, neither **y** nor a clean\n",
        "metric is available.\n",
        "\n",
        "## What changed with pretrained models?\n",
        "\n",
        "### Opaque Training\n",
        "Pretrained models are trained on very large datasets independent of our application. Those can be artificial as is the case for TabPFN, real data (GPT) or hybrids (RealTabPFN).\n",
        "\n",
        "The training data is no longer something we control or even observe — it lives entirely on the model provider's side. At inference time we only supply a context (which, for an LLM, is just the prompt):\n",
        "\n",
        "```{mermaid}\n",
        "---\n",
        "config:\n",
        "  theme: neutral\n",
        "  layout: elk\n",
        "---\n",
        "flowchart LR\n",
        "    subgraph vendor [Black Box]\n",
        "        XP[\"X_pretrain <br> ???\"] --> M[Pretrained model]\n",
        "    end\n",
        "    XC[\"X_context <br> e.g. prompt\"] --> M\n",
        "    M --> Y[Prediction]\n",
        "\n",
        "    style XP stroke:#b91c1c,stroke-dasharray: 5 5,color:#b91c1c\n",
        "    style vendor fill:#f3f4f6,stroke:#9ca3af,color:#1f2937\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "While there is clear advantages to this approach, such as zero-shot learning, transfer learning and much better predictions for small datasets, it also comes at a cost.\n",
        "\n",
        "Firstly, if prediction quality is inadequate, we are severly limited in what we can realistically do to improve the performance. In the case of LLM's this boils down to improve the prompt, enrich with better context or fine-tuning, in case of smaller models.\n",
        "\n",
        "Secondly, as we don't know what the model saw during training it is hard to reason over where it may fail in the future. It is well known \n",
        "\n",
        "### Test data contamination\n",
        "\n",
        "In the classical setup, train, test, and production data are three disjoint slices of the same world: we control all three and can guarantee they don't overlap. With a pretrained model, the training set is gigantic, opaque, and likely overlaps with *both* our test set and our production data — but we don't know by how much:"
      ],
      "id": "fc23c381"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 6,
        "fig-height": 5
